				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>This is a list of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Internet_socket&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Internet socket (page does not exist)">Internet socket</a> <a href="/w/index.php?title=Port_number&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Port number (page does not exist)">port numbers</a> used by protocols of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Transport_Layer&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Transport Layer (page does not exist)">Transport Layer</a> of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Internet_Protocol_Suite&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Internet Protocol Suite (page does not exist)">Internet Protocol Suite</a> for the establishment of host-to-host connectivity.
</p><p>Originally, these port numbers were used by the <a href="/wiki/Network_Control_Program" title="Network Control Program">Network Control Program</a> (NCP) and two ports were needed as transmission was done at half duplex.  As <a href="/wiki/Transmission_Control_Protocol" title="Transmission Control Protocol">Transmission Control Protocol</a> (TCP) and <a href="/wiki/User_Datagram_Protocol" title="User Datagram Protocol">User Datagram Protocol</a> (UDP) were adopted, only one port was needed. The even numbered ports were dropped.  This is why some even numbers in the well-known port number range are unassigned.  TCP and UDP port numbers are also used for the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Stream_Control_Transmission_Protocol&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Stream Control Transmission Protocol (page does not exist)">Stream Control Transmission Protocol</a> (SCTP), and the <a href="/wiki/Datagram_Congestion_Control_Protocol" title="Datagram Congestion Control Protocol">Datagram Congestion Control Protocol</a> (DCCP). SCTP and DCCP services usually use a port number that matches the service of the corresponding TCP or UDP implementation if they exist.
The <a href="/wiki/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority" title="Internet Assigned Numbers Authority">Internet Assigned Numbers Authority</a> (IANA) is responsible for maintaining the official assignments of port numbers for specific uses.<sup id="cite_ref-IANA_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IANA-1">[1]</a></sup> However, many unofficial uses of both well-known and registered port numbers occur in practice.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Well-known_ports">Well-known ports</span></h2>
<p>The port numbers in the range from 0 to 1023 are the <i>well-known ports</i>. They are used by system processes that provide widely used types of network services. On <a href="/w/index.php?title=Unix-like&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Unix-like (page does not exist)">Unix-like</a> operating systems, a process must execute with <a href="/wiki/Superuser" title="Superuser">superuser</a> privileges to be able to bind a <a href="/w/index.php?title=Network_socket&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Network socket (page does not exist)">network socket</a> to an <a href="/wiki/IP_address" title="IP address">IP address</a> using one of the well-known ports.

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Dynamic.2C_private_or_ephemeral_ports">Dynamic, private or ephemeral ports</span></h2>
<p>The range 49152–65535 (2<sup>15</sup>+2<sup>14</sup> to 2<sup>16</sup>−1) – above the registered ports – contains dynamic or private ports that cannot be registered with IANA.<sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">[144]</a></sup> This range is used for custom or temporary purposes and for automatic allocation of <a href="/wiki/Ephemeral_port" title="Ephemeral port">ephemeral ports</a>.
